post_text:
It’s almost the start of a new school year and Oakland Park Traditional Alternative School wants to help students get ready for a remote learning environment. On Saturday, September 5th from 1:00 to 3:00 pm., the school will host a "Drive Thru Back to School Drive" to help students Gear Up for the new school year.

Be sure to come early, the event will feature free backpacks, and school supplies while they last. Cars will pull through a designated area to receive their supplies, along with free snack bags and ice-cream. All CCS students are welcome. Teacher and parent volunteers and members from the Columbus Police Recruiting will be on site to say hello and provide best wishes for a great school year.

Remember to wear your mask and don’t forget to social distance while on site; there will be plenty of sanitizer available to ensure a safe event. The 2020-2021 school year gets underway on September 8, fully remote. #OurCCS

post_text: How do we re-define success for our students? As Columbus City Schools embarked on its journey to disrupt the status quo, a historic disruption in our way of life created more obstacles than expected. With a strong sense of urgency, CCS forged ahead to create a lasting vision for our students. People from all walks of life in our district are coming together to help our schools and our students rise above and build something strong and lasting. This Columbus City Schools story arrives this fall. #OurCCS

post_text:
District Statement on Fall Sports and Activities:

All Columbus City Schools in-person sports and extracurricular activities remain suspended until public health conditions improve. This decision is based on local guidance from Columbus Public Health officials and the Ohio Public Health Advisory Alert System which shows Franklin County at the “red” level. We will continue to evaluate and monitor our decisions on how best to serve students as we begin the school year in a completely virtual environment. When we receive guidance that it is safe to resume in-person sports activities, CCS will engage with the Office of Student Activities, principals, athletic directors, and coaches to determine the best course of action for our students and our teams.
shared_text:

District Statement on Fall Sports and Activities
text:
District Statement on Fall Sports and Activities:

All Columbus City Schools in-person sports and extracurricular activities remain suspended until public health conditions improve. This decision is based on local guidance from Columbus Public Health officials and the Ohio Public Health Advisory Alert System which shows Franklin County at the “red” level. We will continue to evaluate and monitor our decisions on how best to serve students as we begin the school year in a completely virtual environment. When we receive guidance that it is safe to resume in-person sports activities, CCS will engage with the Office of Student Activities, principals, athletic directors, and coaches to determine the best course of action for our students and our teams.

post_text:
Families with K- 12 kids who received free or reduced-price meals in Ohio qualify for the Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) card as a result of the COVID-19 school closure.

If you have NOT received your P-EBT card in the mail, and if your address has changed recently, you MUST update your child’s contact information using the Annual Update feature via the Infinite Campus Parent Portal by Thursday, July 16.

If as of May 1st, the District had your most current address on record, your information has already been shared with the Ohio Department of Job and Family Services.

In this case, if you have not received your P-EBT card, you MUST call the Ohio Department of Jobs and Family Services for further assistance at 1-866-244-0071. Translators will be available to answer your questions. You can also log onto www.ohioPEBT.org to learn more.

Registration Now Open for the CCS K-12 Digital Academy

Columbus City Schools
July 13 at 8:30 PM ·

Registration for the 2020-2021 Columbus City Schools self-paced, completely virtual Digital Academy (K-12) begins today through Saturday, August 1st via the Parent Portal.

Columbus City Schools families who may not want to send their students to school in-person can choose to have their students attend the all-virtual K-12 Digital Academy. The curriculum will be self-paced so students can go as quickly or as slow as they need to complete the work to earn credits. CCS staff will work with families to create personalized learning experiences for Digital Academy students. #OurCCS

For more information, please click below.

post_text:
In the wake of the killing of George Floyd, the Obama Foundation and MBK Alliance are organizing an emergency town hall series that will provide a safe space for boys and young men of color to be heard, connect and discuss police reform.

Playon Patrick, five time winner of the City of Columbus’ annual Dr. Martin Luther King Jr Youth Oratorical Contest and 2020 graduate of Fort Hayes High School, has been selected to perform a spoken word during the event.

As part of the Department of Neighborhoods, MBK Village is focused on supporting the success and engagement of boys and young men of color in our community.

You can watch this online event TODAY at 5:00 p.m. here: https://www.facebook.com/MBKAlliance/

Starting today, Columbus Metropolitan Library will offer limited computer access at two locations:

Linden Branch | 2223 Cleveland Ave.
Martin Luther King Branch | 1467 E. Long St.

A limited number of computers will be available for 50-minute use, and customers can print, copy, fax and scan. No browsing or checkout of materials will be available at this time; however, if you have items ready for pickup at these two locations, they will be checked out for you in the branch. Hours of operation at these two branches will be the same as those listed above for curbside pickup. You can learn more at the link below.

shared_text:
Ethiopian Tewahedo Social Services-ETSS
May 21 at 11:29 PM ·

Tonight we held our 2020 Michael Austin Award ceremony via Zoom. The award honors the legacy of Michael Austin and the impact he had on ETSS Youth Programs. Applicants must have participated in ETSS Youth Programs, be a senior in high school and complete an application process. This year the committee selected three winners. Our second honoree is Tara Odari. Tara joined our Achieve More & Prosper Program in 2018 and was the Emcee for the 2019 Youth Summit. She is graduating from Northland High School and will attend The Ohio State University in the fall. We are so impressed with her desire to give back to her community. Congratulations, Tara Odari!

To mark the end of the school year and inspire Ohio’s youth to seek leadership opportunities, Big Brothers Big Sisters has organized a Strong Youth Strong Communities Virtual Forum tomorrow, Friday, May 22nd at 10 AM.

Special guests include Ohio Governor Mike DeWine and former Cincinnati Bengal Anthony Munoz, along with Darrell Green, and Aeneas Williams of the Pro Football Hall of Fame; and Iman McFarland, former women’s basketball star at the University of North Carolina.
text:
To mark the end of the school year and inspire Ohio’s youth to seek leadership opportunities, Big Brothers Big Sisters has organized a Strong Youth Strong Communities Virtual Forum tomorrow, Friday, May 22nd at 10 AM.

Special guests include Ohio Governor Mike DeWine and former Cincinnati Bengal Anthony Munoz, along with Darrell Green, and Aeneas Williams of the Pro Football Hall of Fame; and Iman McFarland, former women’s basketball star at the University of North Carolina.

post_text: #CCSGrad2020
shared_text:
CCSOH.US
Columbus City Council, Columbus Youth Council & Community Partners To Host Virtual Prom

Columbus City Schools
May 18 at 7:00 PM ·

Columbus City Council, in partnership with Columbus City Schools, Orange Barrel Media and Radio One, will host a virtual prom for the Class of 2020! #OurCCS

Power 107.5 will host the LIVE, CITY-WIDE "Virtual High School Prom" on-air, online and on social media via Instagram @powercolumbus on Saturday, May 23, 2020, from 7PM to midnight. The 2020 Columbus Prom king and queen will also be crowned at the event.

Leading up to the night of the prom, students have the opportunity to compete in the Virtual Prom “Dance Off.” Beginning today, students can post a video to Instagram showing off their best Prom dance moves, name their High School in the caption and use the hashtag #Power614VirtualProm in the post to compete. During the virtual prom, DJ Mr. King will announce winners of the “Dance Off” who will receive a special prize.

shared_text:
Columbus City Council was live.
April 16 at 8:00 PM ·

During this health crisis, one of the primary disruptions for families has been the closure of schools. In this environment, it is vital that we continue to provide the basics like proper nutrition and academic enrichment while students are at home. We want to share information about what resources continue to be available to students and families through CCS and to answer questions.

Pro Tem Elizabeth Brown will be joined by Superintendent Dr. Talisa Dixon and Chief Engagement Officer Alesia Gillison.

All interested citizens are invited to participate and should send in their questions relating to this event to townhall@columbus.gov by noon on Thursday, April 16th. There will also be limited opportunities to ask questions during the event through Facebook Live.
